The following assumptions were made regarding the financial plan:
&nbsp;
* Predicted sales growth of 20\$
&nbsp;
* Constant dividend payout ratio
&nbsp;
* Predicted increase in the cost proportional to sales

Now, let us compute the increase in the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Increase in Sales}&=\text{Sales}\times\text{Rate of Increase}\\[12pt]
&={\$49,000}\times{20\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$9,800}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The increase in the sales amounts to \$9,800.**

Now, let us compute the projected sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Sales}&=\text{Sales}+\text{Increase in Sales}\\[12pt]
&={\$49,000}+{\$9,800}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$58,800}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected sales is \$58,800.**

Now, let us compute the percentage of cost in proportion to the sales:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Percentage of Cost}&=\frac{\text{Cost}}{\text{Sales}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$40,300}{\$49,000}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.82}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{82\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The percentage of cost in proportion to the sales is 82\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected cost:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Cost}&=\text{Projected Sales}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$58,800}\times{82\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$48,216}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected cost is \$48,216.**

Now, let us compute the projected taxable income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Taxable Income}&=\text{Projected Sales}-\text{Projected Cost}\\[12pt]
&={\$58,800}-{\$48,216}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$10,584}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected Taxable income is \$10,584.**

Now, let us compute the taxes:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Taxes}&=\text{Taxable Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$10,584}\times{22\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,328.48}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected taxes is \$2,328.48.**

Now, let us compute the projected net income:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Net Income}&=\text{Taxable Income}-\text{Taxes}\\[12pt]
&={\$10,584}-{\$2,328.48}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$8,255.52}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected net income is \$8,255.52.**

Now, let us compute the dividend payout ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Dividend Payout Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Dividend}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$2,400}{\$6,786}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.35}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{35\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The dividend payout ratio is 35\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected dividend:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Dividend}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$8,255.52}\times{35\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$2,889.43}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected dividend is \$2,889.43.**

Now, let us compute the retention ratio:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Retention Ratio}&=\frac{\text{Retained Earnings}}{\text{Net Income}}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\frac{\$4,386}{\$6,786}\times100\\[12pt]
&={0.65}\times100\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{65\%}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The retention ratio is 65\%.**

Now, let us compute the projected retained earnings:
&nbsp;
$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Projected Retained Earnings}&=\text{Net Income}\times\text{Rate}\\[12pt]
&={\$8,255.52}\times{65\%}\\[12pt]
&=\boxed{\$5,366.09}\\
\end{aligned}$$
&nbsp;
**The projected addition to the retained earnings is \$5,366.09.**

### Compute the projected sales.

The projected sales are calculated by multiplying the current sales with the percentage growth. The percentage growth is 20%, or the projected sales will be 120% for next year.
$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Sales}&= \text{Current Sales} \times \text{Projected Increase in Sales}\\[15pt]
&= \$49,000.00 \times 120\%\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$58,800.00}}

\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected sales for next year are **$58,800.00**.

Therefore, the percentage of the cost of sales from sales is as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Percentage of Cost of Sales from Sales}&= \dfrac{ \$40,300.00}{\$49,000.00}\\[15pt]
&= 0.8224 \times 100\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{82.24\%}}


\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the percentage of the cost of sales from the sales is **82.25%**.

Therefore, the projected cost of sales is as follows.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Projected Cost of Sales}&= \text{82.24\%} \times 58,800.00\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$48,375.12}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected cost of sales is **$48,375.12**.

### Compute the business tax.

The business t ax is treated as operating cost, which is deducted from the taxable income to compute the net income.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Business Tax}&= \text{Taxable Income} \times \text{Tax Rate}\\[15pt]
&= \$10,424.88  \times 22\% \\[15pt]
&=\boxed{\textbf{\$2,293.47}}
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore, the projected business tax is **$2,293.47**.

### Compute the projected net income using the Pro Forma income statement.

After computing the projected cost of sales and business tax, we can now calculate the projected net income.

$$
\begin{array}{c}
\textbf{Cardinal, Inc.}\\
\text{Pro Forma}\\
\text{Income Statement}
\end{array}
$$

$$
\begin{array}{lr}
\textbf{Description}&\underline{\textbf{Amount}}\\[10pt]
\text{Sales}&\$58,800.00\\
\text{Cost of Sales}&\underline{48,375.12}\\
\text{Taxable Income}&10,424.88\\
\text{Taxes(22\%)}&\underline{2,293.47}\\
\textbf{Net Income}&\underline{\underline{\$8,131.41}}
\end{array}
$$

Therefore, the net income is **$8,131.41**.

### Compute the projected addition to the retained earnings.

The retained earnings are calculated by multiplying the retention ratio with the net income.

$$
\begin{aligned}
\textbf{Retained Earnings}&= \text{Retention Ratio} \times \text{Net Income}\\[15pt]
&=64.63\% \times \$8,131.41\\[15pt]
&= \boxed{\textbf{\$5,255.33}}


\end{aligned}
$$
Therefore, the projected addition to the retained earnings is **$5,255.33**.
